{
  "style": "APA",
  "texts": [
    "Grammaticality judgement is a central method to assess linguistic representation competence.",
    "Chomsky (1986) highlighted that evidence for linguistic theorizing largely depends on \"the judgements of native speakers\".",
    "While there are other sources of evidence, like speech corpus or acquisition sequences (Devitt, 2006), formal linguists typically favor native speakers' grammaticality intuitions.",
    "The prevailing assumption is that our language knowledge comprises abstract rules and principles, forming intuitions about sentence well-formedness (Graves et al. 1973; Chomsky 1980; Fodor 1981).",
    "However, relying on grammaticality judgments to frame linguistic theories isn't without dispute."
  ],
  "correct_citations": [
